Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Space Industry Section, Machinery and </F>
Information Industries Bureau, Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry] 
  [Text] Thanks to the progress made in international space 
development efforts in recent years, topics related to space 
technology are becoming increasingly familiar to the people. For 
example, the images of cloud patterns over and around Japan, 
which are sent by the meteorological satellite "Himawari," are 
shown on television every day. The number of households 
subscribing to satellite broadcasting service exceeds 4 million. 
In addition, we are communicating with people in foreign 
countries using the international telephone service offered via 
communications satellites. In recent years, the use of the 
global positioning system (GPS) satellite launched by the United 
States is expanding from use on ships to use in cars, as well as 
to portable use by individuals. 
  The space industry has been promoting the use of the space 
technology that makes it possible to offer these services. The 
industry comprises the space hardware production industry which 
manufactures satellites and rockets, etc.; the space utilization 
industry which offers broadcasting, communications, 
meteorological and earth observation services; and the 
space-related service industry which offers various services, 
including database services using satellites. As their markets 
continue to expand, these industries are beginning to experience 
increased competition on the international market. Under these 
circumstances, the Japanese space industry is experiencing a 
turning point that is expected to continue up to around the year 
2000. 
  The Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) has 
been promoting a number of programs aimed at encouraging the use 
of space technology and services in Japan. These programs have 
been promoted through increased cooperation with the 
organizations devoted to promoting the use of space technology 
and other space-related establishments in foreign countries. In 
promoting these programs, the ministry took into consideration 
the recent progress being made in global information exchange 
services and the urgency of tackling the problem of the earth's 
deteriorating environment. 
  Figure 1 [not reproduced] outlines the current system in 
Japan aimed at promoting space development and the use of space 
technology. Table 1 explains the contents of MITI's budgets for 
space development in FY91 and 92. This paper will outline MITI's 
policy for promoting domestic space industry. 



